Millennials seem highly averse to Gen X "I hate my wife" humor. E.g. a: "You love each other so much now, but let's see how you'll be in ten years" is taken as rooting for a marriage to "fail". But many older couples lacking affection are still each other's world, albeit hiddenly

It's probably a good sign (wow, finally Millennials do ONE fucking thing right!), as it shows belief in the potential for unrelenting Eros, passion, in-loveness against tedium. Evola himself explained the loss of these in older relationships represents a decay. Have hope in Amor!

Still they harbor cruelty for the outwardly cold Gen X and boomer couples who flaunt indifference and hide gentleness in such assumptions, even if out of idealism. Only The Zoomer walks in clarity, host and master of all generations (I use "The Zoomer" as Junger did "The Worker")
